assumptions:
  - "faraday-follow_redirects 0.5.0 registers as 'Faraday::FollowRedirects::Middleware' and exposes a :limit option that maps to the hop cap"
  - "ActiveRecord's serialize :expected_status_codes, coder: JSON round-trips nil, arrays of integers, and empty arrays correctly through a text column"
  - "Rails 8 form_with's check_box helper uses the model's boolean attribute correctly when the column default is true"
  - "The plan's 'expected_status_codes is full override not additive' semantic is what operators actually want — verifiable via the form helper text which says 'ONLY those codes count as up'"

specifications:
  - "HttpChecker.check takes url positionally plus follow_redirects: keyword (default true)"
  - "HttpChecker registers Faraday::FollowRedirects::Middleware after SsrfGuard in the Faraday stack; a structural spec pins the ordering (ssrf_index < redirect_index)"
  - "Redirect hop cap is HttpChecker::MAX_REDIRECTS = 3, which matches faraday-follow_redirects default (intentional — not overridden)"
  - "ContentMatchChecker.check accepts follow_redirects: and passes it through to HttpChecker.check"
  - "CheckDispatcher passes site.follow_redirects to both :http and :content_match branches"
  - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status takes (site, result) instead of just (result) so it can read site.expected_status_codes"
  - "derive_status order: error_message present -> :down; metadata[:matched] == false -> :down; status_code nil -> :up; expected_status_codes present -> in?(list) ? :up : :down; else 200..399 check"
  - "expected_status_codes is an OVERRIDE when set — 202 is :down if the list is [200, 301] even though 202 is in the default 200-399 range"
  - "Site#expected_status_codes= parses comma-separated strings into integer arrays; blank string -> nil; invalid tokens -> parse error recorded by a validator, not raised"
  - "Site validates expected_status_codes integers are in 100..599 per element, and rejects range-style strings like '200-299'"
  - "Site#follow_redirects has database default true and NOT NULL; existing pre-Slice-8 rows backfill to true"
  - "SiteForm::HttpOptionsFieldsComponent renders a follow_redirects checkbox and expected_status_codes text input; the type_fields_component dispatcher renders it for :http and :content_match (both check types use HttpChecker under the hood)"

deviations_from_plan: >
  HttpChecker.check signature has follow_redirects as a keyword arg but
  NOT expected_status_codes as the plan's Slice 8 text suggested. The
  plan text was inconsistent — it said HttpChecker takes the kwarg but
  also said derive_status reads site.expected_status_codes (health
  classification in the job per decision 3). Went with decision 3's
  rule: HttpChecker returns raw status_code; the job reads the
  allowlist from the Site. Less coupling between the checker and the
  Site schema.

trade_offs: >
  ContentMatchChecker and HttpChecker both accept follow_redirects as
  a boolean kwarg rather than extracting a shared "HttpOptions" struct.
  Cost: the second wrapper (ContentMatchChecker) has to thread the
  kwarg through. Benefit: no new value type, no migration when a third
  HTTP option lands in a future slice. Revisit if the threading grows
  past ~3 kwargs.

  expected_status_codes is stored as a JSON-serialized text column rather
  than a Postgres array or a separate join table. SQLite doesn't have
  array columns natively; JSON is the Rails-idiomatic fallback. Cost: no
  SQL-level querying ("find sites that accept 404"). Benefit: zero
  coupling to Postgres and the column round-trips transparently. Nobody
  is querying Site by its expected-codes list anyway — it's read on
  every check and the read is O(1) list membership.

  The ordering-assertion spec reaches into Faraday's internal builder
  handlers list (conn.builder.handlers.map(&:klass)). That's implementation-
  dependent API. Cost: a Faraday 3.x upgrade may break this spec. Benefit:
  the ordering invariant — SsrfGuard MUST be before follow_redirects — is
  security-critical and needs to turn red automatically, not rely on code-
  review vigilance. Accepted.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "faraday-follow_redirects ~> 0.5 (Faraday::FollowRedirects::Middleware, :limit option)"
    - "ActiveRecord::Base.serialize (coder: JSON)"
    - "Site#follow_redirects -> Boolean"
    - "Site#expected_status_codes -> Array<Integer> | nil"
  published:
    - "HttpChecker.check(url, follow_redirects: true) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "ContentMatchChecker.check(url:, pattern:, follow_redirects: true) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status(site, result) -> Symbol (private, internal refactor)"
    - "Site#expected_status_codes= (accepts String | Array<Integer> | nil)"
    - "Site#expected_status_codes_for_display -> String (comma-joined)"
    - "Site#follow_redirects= (boolean writer)"
    - "SiteForm::HttpOptionsFieldsComponent.new(form:, site:) -> component"
    - "HttpChecker::MAX_REDIRECTS -> 3"
    - "Site::HTTP_STATUS_RANGE -> 100..599"

self_review:
  tests: >
    Extended spec/services/http_checker_spec.rb with three new contexts:
    follow_redirects: true + 301 chain → final 200 and final body,
    follow_redirects: false + 301 → raw 301, and a structural middleware
    ordering assertion. Extended spec/services/content_match_checker_spec.rb
    with the follow_redirects-through passthrough (stubs updated to match
    the new signature). Extended spec/services/check_dispatcher_spec.rb
    with new expectations that :http and :content_match pass
    follow_redirects. Added two job spec contexts for expected_status_codes
    allowlist match and miss. Extended site_spec.rb with 9 parsing/validation
    cases and a follow_redirects default case.
  consistency: >
    Matches the existing checker class-method entrypoint pattern. The
    SiteForm::HttpOptionsFieldsComponent follows the same leaf-component
    shape as SslFieldsComponent / TcpFieldsComponent / DnsFieldsComponent
    / ContentMatchFieldsComponent — same initialize signature, attr_reader,
    field_error helper. The parsing setter is one of three custom setters
    in the Site model; naming pattern matches standard Rails (attribute=
    override + super).
  metz: >
    Measured. http_checker.rb is 69 lines, 7 methods. check is 5 body
    lines + rescue. connection gains one line (the conditional
    f.response :follow_redirects). site.rb is 115 lines, 15 methods
    including private helpers — over the 100-line Metz limit. Two of the
    new methods (parse_expected_status_codes 9 body lines,
    validate_expected_status_codes 11 body lines) are the size outliers.
    Splitting validate_expected_status_codes into two validators (one for
    parse error, one for range) is a clean refactor candidate but not
    done mid-slice. Noted as a follow-up for the eventual Site model
    decomposition (likely a post-epic chore).
  duplication: >
    Six SiteForm:: leaf components now — SslFieldsComponent, TcpFieldsComponent,
    DnsFieldsComponent, ContentMatchFieldsComponent, HttpOptionsFieldsComponent,
    TypeFieldsComponent. All share initialize + attr_reader + (on leaves)
    field_error. The base class extraction is overdue; still deferred to
    avoid mid-epic refactor. Filing as a follow-up issue.
  mocking: >
    Middleware ordering spec uses Faraday's internal builder.handlers API
    — the only non-public Faraday surface touched by any spec in the epic.
    Pinned in one spec with a comment so a future Faraday version bump
    surfaces the coupling immediately.
  error_paths: >
    The follow_redirects happy path and the no-follow path are both covered.
    Parse error path for expected_status_codes is covered by six Site spec
    cases (blank, single integer, whitespace, invalid token, range string,
    out-of-range integer). The ordering check is a regression lock on a
    security invariant.
  security: >
    The Faraday middleware ordering (SsrfGuard before follow_redirects) is
    the critical invariant — a redirect chain can go from a public host to
    an internal IP in one hop, and SsrfGuard must re-validate on every hop.
    The structural spec prevents accidental reordering during refactors.
    The 3-hop cap bounds the blast radius of any single check.
  performance: >
    Redirect following adds up to 3 extra HTTP round trips per check when
    the remote serves redirects. Bounded and cheap on a 60s cadence. No
    regex compilation, no dynamic class generation.
  api: >
    Additive. HttpChecker.check gains a kwarg with a default, existing
    callers unaffected. ContentMatchChecker.check gains a kwarg with a
    default. PerformCheckJob#derive_status signature changed from (result)
    to (site, result); this is private so callers are the job itself.
    Site#expected_status_codes, Site#follow_redirects, Site::HTTP_STATUS_RANGE,
    HttpChecker::MAX_REDIRECTS, SiteForm::HttpOptionsFieldsComponent are new.
  dead_code: >
    None. faraday-follow_redirects is required at the top of HttpChecker.
    HttpOptionsFieldsComponent is rendered by the dispatcher for :http and
    :content_match. MAX_REDIRECTS is referenced in the connection method
    and in the form ERB. Custom setter and display helper are both used
    by the form component.

